[src:date-fns-toolkit/global-objects-date] The following examples show how to determine the elapsed time between two JavaScript dates in milliseconds.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/global-objects-date] Due to the differing lengths of days (due to daylight saving changeover), months, and years, expressing elapsed time in units greater than hours, minutes, and seconds requires addressing a number of issues, and should be thoroughly researched before being attempted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/global-objects-date] In this case, it's important to return only an integer—so a simple division won't do.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/global-objects-date] It's also important to only return actually elapsed seconds.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The **Gregorian calendar** is the calendar used in most parts of the world.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] It went into effect in October 1582 following the papal bull *Inter gravissimas* issued by Pope Gregory XIII, which introduced it as a modification of, and replacement for, the Julian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The rule for leap years is that every year divisible by four is a leap year, except for years that are divisible by 100, except in turn for years also divisible by 400.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, 1800 and 1900 were not leap years, but 1600 and 2000 were leap years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] There were two reasons to establish the Gregorian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] First, the Julian calendar was based on the estimate that the average solar year is exactly 365.25 days long, an overestimate of a little under one day per century, and thus has a leap year every four years without exception.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian reform shortened the average (calendar) year by 0.0075 days to stop the drift of the calendar with respect to the equinoxes.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Second, in the years since the First Council of Nicaea in AD 325, the excess leap days introduced by the Julian algorithm had caused the calendar to drift such that the March equinox was occurring well before its nominal 21 March date.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This date was important to the Christian churches, because it is fundamental to the calculation of the date of Easter.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] To reinstate the association, the reform advanced the date by 10 days: Thursday 4 October 1582 was followed by Friday 15 October 1582.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In addition, the reform also altered the lunar cycle used by the Church to calculate the date for Easter, because astronomical new moons were occurring four days before the calculated dates.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The reform was adopted initially by the Catholic countries of Europe and their overseas possessions.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Over the next three centuries, the Protestant and Eastern Orthodox countries also gradually moved to what they called the "**Improved calendar**", with Greece being the last European country to adopt the calendar (for civil use only) in 1923.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] However, many Orthodox churches continue to use the Julian calendar for religious rites and the dating of major feasts.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] To unambiguously specify a date during the transition period (in contemporary documents or in history texts), both notations were given, tagged as "Old Style" or "New Style" as appropriate.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] During the 20th century, most non-Western countries also adopted the calendar, at least for civil purposes.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian calendar, like the Julian calendar, is a solar calendar with 12 months of 28–31 days each.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The year in both calendars consists of 365 days, with a leap day being added to February in the leap years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The months and length of months in the Gregorian calendar are the same as for the Julian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The only difference is that the Gregorian calendar omits a leap day in *three* centurial years every 400 years and leaves the leap day unchanged in the fourth.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A leap year normally occurs every four years: the leap day, historically, was inserted by doubling 24 February – there were indeed two days dated 24 February.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] However, for many years it has been customary to put the extra day at the end of the month of February, adding a 29 February for the leap day.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Before the 1969 revision of its General Roman Calendar, the Catholic Church delayed February feasts after the 23rd by one day in leap years; masses celebrated according to the previous calendar still reflect this delay.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Gregorian years are identified by consecutive year numbers.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A calendar date is fully specified by the year (numbered according to a calendar era, in this case *Anno Domini* or Common Era), the month (identified by name or number), and the day of the month (numbered sequentially starting from 1).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Although the calendar year currently runs from 1 January to 31 December, at previous times year numbers were based on a different starting point within the calendar .
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Calendar cycles (ignoring lunar and Easter calculations) repeat completely every 400 years, which equals 146,097 days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Of these 400 years, 303 are regular years of 365 days and 97 are leap years of 366 days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian calendar was a reform of the Julian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] It was instituted by the papal bull *Inter gravissimas* dated 24 February 1582 by Pope Gregory XIII, after whom the calendar is named.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The motivation for the adjustment was to bring the date for the celebration of Easter to the time of year in which it was celebrated when it was introduced by the early Church.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The error in the Julian calendar (its assumption that there are exactly 365.25 days in a year) had led to the date of the equinox according to the calendar drifting from the observed reality, and thus an error had been introduced into the calculation of the date of Easter.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Because the date of Easter is a function – the *computus* – of the date of the spring equinox in the northern hemisphere, the Catholic Church considered the increasing divergence between the canonical date of the equinox and observed reality to be unacceptable.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Easter is celebrated on the Sunday after the ecclesiastical full moon on or after 21 March, which was adopted as an approximation to the March equinox.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] European scholars had been well aware of the calendar drift since the early medieval period.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Bede, writing in the 8th century, showed that the accumulated error in his time was more than three days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] 1200, estimated the error at seven or eight days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] 1300, was aware of the need for calendar reform.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] An attempt to go forward with such a reform was undertaken by Pope Sixtus IV, who in 1475 invited Regiomontanus to the Vatican for this purpose.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] However, the project was interrupted by the death of Regiomontanus shortly after his arrival in Rome.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The increase of astronomical knowledge and the precision of observations towards the end of the 15th century made the question more pressing.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Numerous publications over the following decades called for a calendar reform, among them two papers sent to the Vatican by the University of Salamanca in 1515 and 1578, but the project was not taken up again until the 1540s, and implemented only under Pope Gregory XIII (r.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In 1545, the Council of Trent authorised Pope Paul III to reform the calendar, requiring that the date of the vernal equinox be restored to that which it held at the time of the First Council of Nicaea in 325 and that an alteration to the calendar be designed to prevent future drift.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This would allow for more consistent and accurate scheduling of the feast of Easter.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In 1577, a *Compendium* was sent to expert mathematicians outside the reform commission for comments.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Some of these experts, including Giambattista Benedetti and Giuseppe Moleto, believed Easter should be computed from the true motions of the Sun and Moon, rather than using a tabular method, but these recommendations were not adopted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The reform adopted was a modification of a proposal made by the Calabrian doctor Aloysius Lilius (or Lilio).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Lilius's proposal included reducing the number of leap years in four centuries from 100 to 97, by making three out of four centurial years common instead of leap years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] He also produced an original and practical scheme for adjusting the epacts of the Moon when calculating the annual date of Easter, solving a long-standing obstacle to calendar reform.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Ancient tables provided the Sun's mean longitude.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The German mathematician Christopher Clavius, the architect of the Gregorian calendar, noted that the tables agreed neither on the time when the Sun passed through the vernal equinox nor on the length of the mean tropical year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian leap year rule (97 leap years in 400 years) was put forward by Petrus Pitatus of Verona in 1560.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] He noted that it is consistent with the tropical year of the Alfonsine tables and with the mean tropical year of Copernicus (*De revolutionibus*) and Erasmus Reinhold (*Prutenic tables*).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The three mean tropical years in Babylonian sexagesimals as the excess over 365 days (the way they would have been extracted from the tables of mean longitude) were 0;14,33,9,57 (Alfonsine), 0;14,33,11,12 (Copernicus) and 0;14,33,9,24 (Reinhold).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] All values are the same to two sexagesimal places (0;14,33, equal to decimal 0.2425) and this is also the mean length of the Gregorian year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Thus Pitatus's solution would have commended itself to the astronomers.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] First, he proposed a correction to the length of the year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The mean tropical year is 365.24219 days long.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A commonly used value in Lilius's time, from the Alfonsine tables, is 365.2425463 days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] As the average length of a Julian year is 365.25 days, the Julian year is almost 11 minutes longer than the mean tropical year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The discrepancy results in a drift of about three days every 400 years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Lilius's proposal resulted in an average year of 365.2425 days .
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] At the time of Gregory's reform, there had already been a drift of 10 days since the Council of Nicaea, resulting in the vernal equinox falling on 10 or 11 March instead of the ecclesiastically fixed date of 21 March, and if unreformed it would have drifted further.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Lilius proposed that the 10-day drift should be corrected by deleting the Julian leap day on each of its ten occurrences over a period of forty years, thereby providing for a gradual return of the equinox to 21 March.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Lilius's work was expanded upon by Christopher Clavius in a closely argued, 800-page volume.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] He would later defend his and Lilius's work against detractors.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Clavius's opinion was that the correction should take place in one move, and it was this advice that prevailed with Gregory.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The second component consisted of an approximation that would provide an accurate yet simple, rule-based calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Lilius's formula was a 10-day correction to revert the drift since the Council of Nicaea, and the imposition of a leap day in only 97 years in 400 rather than in 1 year in 4.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The proposed rule was that "years divisible by 100 would be leap years only if they were divisible by 400 as well".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The 19-year cycle used for the lunar calendar required revision because the astronomical new moon was, at the time of the reform, four days before the calculated new moon.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] It was to be corrected by one day every 300 or 400 years (8 times in 2,500 years) along with corrections for the years that were no longer leap years (i.e.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] 1700, 1800, 1900, 2100, etc.) In fact, a new method for computing the date of Easter was introduced.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The method proposed by Lilius was revised somewhat in the final reform.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] When the new calendar was put in use, the error accumulated in the 13 centuries since the Council of Nicaea was corrected by a deletion of 10 days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Julian calendar day Thursday, 4 October 1582 was followed by the first day of the Gregorian calendar, Friday, 15 October 1582 (the cycle of weekdays was not affected).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A month after decreeing the reform, the pope (with a brief of 3 April 1582) granted to one Antoni Lilio the exclusive right to publish the calendar for a period of ten years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The *Lunario Novo secondo la nuova riforma* was printed by Vincenzo Accolti, one of the first calendars printed in Rome after the reform, notes at the bottom that it was signed with papal authorization and by Lilio (*Con licentia delli Superiori... et permissu Ant(onii) Lilij*).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The papal brief was revoked on 20 September 1582, because Antonio Lilio proved unable to keep up with the demand for copies.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Although Gregory's reform was enacted in the most solemn of forms available to the Church, the bull had no authority beyond the Catholic Church (of which he was the supreme religious authority) and the Papal States (which he personally ruled).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The changes that he was proposing were changes to the civil calendar, which required adoption by the civil authorities in each country to have legal effect.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The bull *Inter gravissimas* became the law of the Catholic Church in 1582, but it was not recognised by Protestant churches, Eastern Orthodox churches, Oriental Orthodox churches, and a few others.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Consequently, the days on which Easter and related holidays were celebrated by different Christian churches again diverged.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] On 29 September 1582, Philip II of Spain decreed the change from the Julian to the Gregorian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This affected much of Roman Catholic Europe, as Philip was at the time ruler over Spain and Portugal as well as much of Italy.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In these territories, as well as in the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth and in the Papal States, the new calendar was implemented on the date specified by the bull, with Julian Thursday, 4 October 1582, being followed by Gregorian Friday, 15 October.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Spanish and Portuguese colonies followed somewhat later *de facto* because of delay in communication.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The other major Catholic power of Western Europe, France, adopted the change a few months later: 9 December was followed by 20 December.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Many Protestant countries initially objected to adopting a Catholic innovation; some Protestants feared the new calendar was part of a plot to return them to the Catholic fold.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, the British could not bring themselves to adopt the Catholic system explicitly: the Annexe to their Calendar (New Style) Act 1750 established a computation for the date of Easter that achieved the same result as Gregory's rules, without actually referring to him.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Britain and the British Empire (including the eastern part of what is now the United States) adopted the Gregorian calendar in 1752.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Prior to 1917, Turkey used the lunar Islamic calendar with the Hijri era for general purposes and the Julian calendar for fiscal purposes.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The start of the fiscal year was eventually fixed at 1 March and the year number was roughly equivalent to the Hijri year (see Rumi calendar).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] As the solar year is longer than the lunar year, this originally entailed the use of "escape years" every so often when the number of the fiscal year would jump.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] From 1 March 1917, the fiscal year became Gregorian, rather than Julian.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] On 1 January 1926, the use of the Gregorian calendar was extended to include use for general purposes and the number of the year became the same as in most other countries.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This section always places the intercalary day on 29 February even though it was always obtained by doubling 24 February (the *bissextum* (twice sixth) or bissextile day) until the late Middle Ages.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian calendar is proleptic before 1582 (calculated backwards on the same basis, for years before 1582), and the difference between Gregorian and Julian calendar dates increases by three days every four centuries (all date ranges are inclusive).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The following equation gives the number of days that the Gregorian calendar is ahead of the Julian calendar, called the "secular difference" between the two calendars.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Up to 28 February in the calendar being converted *from*, add one day less or subtract one day more than the calculated value.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Give February the appropriate number of days for the calendar being converted *into*.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] When subtracting days to calculate the Gregorian equivalent of 29 February (Julian), 29 February is discounted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Thus if the calculated value is −4 the Gregorian equivalent of this date is 24 February.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The year used in dates during the Roman Republic and the Roman Empire was the consular year, which began on the day when consuls first entered office—probably 1 May before 222 BC, 15 March from 222 BC and 1 January from 153 BC.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Julian calendar, which began in 45 BC, continued to use 1 January as the first day of the new year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Even though the year used for dates changed, the civil year always displayed its months in the order January to December from the Roman Republican period until the present.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In common usage, 1 January was regarded as New Year's Day and celebrated as such, but, from the 12th century until 1751, the legal year in England began on 25 March (Lady Day).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] So, for example, the Parliamentary record lists the execution of Charles I on 30 January as occurring in 1648 (as the year did not end until 24 March), although later histories adjust the start of the year to 1 January and record the execution as occurring in 1649.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Most Western European countries changed the start of the year to 1 January before they adopted the Gregorian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, Scotland changed the start of the Scottish New Year to 1 January in 1600 (this meant that 1599 was a short year).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] England, Ireland and the British colonies changed the start of the year to 1 January in 1752 (so 1751 was a short year with only 282 days).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Then, in September 1752, the Gregorian calendar was introduced throughout Britain and the British colonies (see the section Adoption).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] These two reforms were implemented by the Calendar (New Style) Act 1750.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In some countries, an official decree or law specifies that the start of the year should be 1 January.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For such countries, a specific date when a "1 January year" became the norm, can be identified.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In other countries, customs varied, and the start of the year moved back and forth as fashion and influence from other countries dictated various customs.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Neither the papal bull nor its attached canons explicitly fix such a date, though the latter states that the "Golden number" of 1752 ends in December and a new year (and new Golden number) begins in January 1753.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Even before 1582, the year sometimes had to be double-dated because of the different beginnings of the year in various countries.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Woolley, writing in his biography of John Dee (1527–1608/9), notes that immediately after 1582 English letter writers "customarily" used "two dates" on their letters, one OS and one NS.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] "Old Style" (O.S.) and "New Style" (N.S.) indicate dating systems before and after a calendar change, respectively.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Usually, this is the change from the Julian calendar to the Gregorian calendar as enacted in various European countries between 1582 and the early 20th century.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In England, Wales, Ireland, and Britain's American colonies, there were two calendar changes, both in 1752.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The first adjusted the start of a new year from Lady Day (25 March) to 1 January (which Scotland had done from 1600), while the second discarded the Julian calendar in favour of the Gregorian calendar, removing 11 days from the September 1752 calendar to do so.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] To accommodate the two calendar changes, writers used dual dating to identify a given day by giving its date according to both styles of dating.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For countries such as Russia where no start of year adjustment took place, O.S. and N.S. simply indicate the Julian and Gregorian dating systems.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Many Eastern Orthodox countries continue to use the older Julian calendar for religious purposes.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Extending the Gregorian calendar backwards to dates preceding its official introduction in a particular jurisdiction produces a proleptic calendar, which should be used with some caution.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For ordinary purposes, the dates of events occurring prior to 15 October 1582 are generally shown as they appeared in the Julian calendar, with the year starting on 1 January, and no conversion to a putative Gregorian equivalents.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, the Battle of Agincourt is universally considered to have been fought on 25 October 1415 which is Saint Crispin's Day.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] But for the period between 15 October 1582 and 14 September 1752 (the date of its legal introduction in the British Empire), a significant risk of misunderstanding arises in English language texts.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Even then, events that happened on the Continent are usually reported in English language histories according to the local convention where the event occurred, so usually the Gregorian calendar.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, the Battle of Blenheim is always given as 13 August 1704.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Confusion may occur when an event affects both.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, William III of England set sail from the Netherlands on 11 November 1688 (Gregorian calendar) and arrived at Brixham in England on 5 November 1688 (Julian calendar).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Europeans sometimes attempt to remember the number of days in each month by memorizing some form of the traditional verse "Thirty Days Hath September".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] It appears in Latin, Italian, French and Portuguese, and belongs to a broad oral tradition but the earliest currently attested form of the poem is the English marginalia inserted into a calendar of saints c.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Variations appeared in *Mother Goose* and continue to be taught at schools.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The unhelpfulness of such involved mnemonics has been parodied as "Thirty days hath September / But all the rest I can't remember" but it has also been called "probably the only sixteenth-century poem most ordinary citizens know by heart".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A common nonverbal alternative is the knuckle mnemonic, considering the knuckles of one's hands as months with 31 days and the lower spaces between them as months with fewer days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Using two hands, one may start from either pinkie knuckle as January and count across, omitting the space between the index knuckles (July and August).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The same procedure can be done using the knuckles of a single hand, returning from the last (July) to the first (August) and continuing through.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A similar mnemonic is to move up a piano keyboard in semitones from an F key, taking the white keys as the longer months and the black keys as the shorter ones.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In conjunction with the system of months, there is a system of weeks.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] A physical or electronic calendar provides conversion from a given date to the weekday and shows multiple dates for a given weekday and month.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Calculating the day of the week is not very simple, because of the irregularities in the Gregorian system.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] When the Gregorian calendar was adopted by each country, the weekly cycle continued uninterrupted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For example, in the case of the few countries that adopted the reformed calendar on the date proposed by Gregory XIII for the calendar's adoption, Friday, 15 October 1582, the preceding date was Thursday, 4 October 1582 (Julian calendar).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Opinions vary about the numbering of the days of the week.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] ISO 8601, in common use worldwide, starts with Monday=1; printed monthly calendar grids often list Mondays in the first (left) column of dates and Sundays in the last.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In North America, the week typically begins on Sunday and ends on Saturday.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The Gregorian calendar improves the approximation made by the Julian calendar by skipping three Julian leap days in every 400 years, giving an average year of 365.2425 mean solar days long.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This approximation has an error of about one day per 3,030 years (NASA: 1 day every 3,333.3 years) with respect to the current value of the mean tropical year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] By any criterion, the Gregorian calendar is substantially more accurate than the 1 day in 128 years error of the Julian calendar (average year 365.25 days).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] In the 19th century, Sir John Herschel proposed a modification to the Gregorian calendar with 969 leap days every 4,000 years, instead of 970 leap days that the Gregorian calendar would insert over the same period.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This would reduce the average year to 365.24225 days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Herschel's proposal would make the year 4000, and multiples thereof, common instead of leap.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] While this modification has often been proposed since, it has never been officially adopted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] On time scales of thousands of years, the Gregorian calendar falls behind the astronomical seasons.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This is because the Earth's speed of rotation is gradually slowing down, which makes each day slightly longer over time (see tidal acceleration and leap second) while the year maintains a more uniform duration.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] This image shows the difference between the Gregorian calendar and the astronomical seasons.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The *y*-axis is the date of the solstice in June and the *x*-axis is Gregorian calendar years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Each point is the date and time of the June solstice in that particular year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] The error shifts by about a quarter of a day per year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] Centurial years are ordinary years, unless they are divisible by 400, in which case they are leap years.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/gregorian-calendar] For instance, these corrections cause 23 December 1903 to be the latest December solstice, and 20 December 2096 to be the earliest solstice—about 2.35 days of variation compared with the astronomical event.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601 applies to these representations and formats: dates, in the Gregorian calendar (including the proleptic Gregorian calendar); times, based on the 24-hour timekeeping system, with optional UTC offset, time intervals, and combinations thereof.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The standard does not assign specific meaning to any element of the dates/times represented: the meaning of any element depends on the context of its use.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Dates and times represented cannot use words that do not have a specified numerical meaning within the standard (thus excluding names of years in the Chinese calendar), or that do not use computer characters (excludes images or sounds).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] In representations that adhere to the ISO 8601 interchange standard, dates and times are arranged such that the greatest temporal term (typically a year) is placed at the left and each successively lesser term is placed to the right of the previous term.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The first edition of the ISO 8601 standard was published as *ISO 8601:1988* in June 1988.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] All editions and parts of ISO 8601 and its predecessors were prepared by, and are under the direct responsibility of, ISO Technical Committee TC 154.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Issued in February 2019, the fourth revision of the standard, ISO 8601-1:2019, represents slightly updated contents of the previous ISO 8601:2004 standard, but is now the first of two parts.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It defines various extensions such as uncertainties or parts of the Extended Date/Time Format (EDTF).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] An amendment to ISO 8601-1 was published in October 2022 featuring minor technical clarifications and attempts to remove ambiguities in definitions.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The most significant change, however, was the reintroduction of the "24:00:00" format to refer to the instant at the *end* of a calendar day.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] An amendment to ISO 8601-2 was published in January 2025.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The standard uses the Gregorian calendar, which "serves as an international standard for civil use".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601 allows Gregorian dates from the introduction of the calendar on 15 October 1582.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For earlier (pre-Gregorian) dates, the calendar may be extended before its introduction (the proleptic Gregorian calendar) by explicit agreement of the parties involved.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Such proleptic dates may not be adjusted to reconcile them with Julian dates.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601 prescribes, as a minimum, a four-digit year [YYYY] to avoid the year 2000 problem.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It therefore represents years from 0000 to 9999, year 0000 being equal to 1 BC and all others AD, similar to astronomical year numbering.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] However, years before 1583 (the first full year following the introduction of the Gregorian calendar) are not automatically allowed by the standard.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Instead, the standard states that "values in the range [0000] through [1582] shall only be used by mutual agreement of the partners in information interchange".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] To represent years before 0000 or after 9999, the standard also permits the expansion of the year representation but only by prior agreement between the sender and the receiver.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] An expanded year representation [±YYYYY] must have an agreed-upon number of extra year digits beyond the four-digit minimum, and it must be prefixed with a + or - sign instead of the more common AD/BC (or CE/BCE) notation; by convention 1 BC is labelled +0000, 2 BC is labeled -0001, and so on.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Calendar date representations are in the form shown in the adjacent box. [YYYY] indicates a four-digit year, 0000 through 9999. [MM] indicates a two-digit month of the year, 01 through 12. [DD] indicates a two-digit day of that month, 01 through 31.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example, "5 April 1981" may be represented as either "1981-04-05" in the *extended format* or "19810405" in the *basic format*.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The standard also allows for calendar dates to be written with reduced precision.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] One may simply write "1981" to refer to that year, "198" to refer to the decade from 1980 to 1989 inclusive, or "19" to refer to the century from 1900 to 1999 inclusive.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Although the standard allows both the "YYYY-MM-DD" and YYYYMMDD formats for complete calendar date representations, if the day [DD] is omitted then only the YYYY-MM format is allowed.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] By disallowing dates of the form YYYYMM, the standard avoids confusion with the truncated representation YYMMDD (still often used).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The 2000 version also allowed writing the truncation "--04-05" to mean "April 5" but the 2004 version does not allow omitting the year when a month is present.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] As a consequence, if 1 January is on a Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday, it is in week 01.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If 1 January is on a Friday, Saturday or Sunday, it is in week 52 or 53 of the previous year (there is no week 00).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] 28 December is always in the last week of its year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The week number can be described by counting the Thursdays: Week 12 contains the 12th Thursday of the year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The *ISO week-numbering year* starts at the first day (Monday) of week 01 and ends at the Sunday before the new ISO year (hence without overlap or gap).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The first ISO week of a year may have up to three days that are actually in the Gregorian calendar year that is ending; if three, they are Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Similarly, the last ISO week of a year may have up to three days that are actually in the Gregorian calendar year that is starting; if three, they are Friday, Saturday, and Sunday.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The Thursday of each ISO week is always in the Gregorian calendar year denoted by the ISO week-numbering year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] An *ordinal date* is an ordinal format for the multiples of a day elapsed since the start of year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It is represented as "YYYY-DDD" (or YYYYDDD), where [YYYY] indicates a year and [DDD] is the "day of year", from 001 through 365 (366 in leap years).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This simple form is preferable for occasions when the arbitrary nature of week and month definitions are more of an impediment than an aid, for instance, when comparing dates from different calendars.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This format is used with simple hardware systems that have a need for a date system, but where including full calendar calculation software may be a significant nuisance.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Earlier versions omitted the T (representing time) in both formats.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] So a time might appear as either "T134730" in the *basic format* or "T13:47:30" in the *extended format*.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601-1:2019 allows the T to be omitted in the extended format, as in "13:47:30", but only allows the T to be omitted in the basic format when there is no risk of confusion with date expressions.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] As of ISO 8601-1:2019/Amd 1:2022, "00:00:00" may be used to refer to *midnight* corresponding to the instant at the beginning of a calendar day; and "24:00:00" to refer to midnight corresponding to the instant at the end of a calendar day.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601-1:2019 as originally published removed "24:00:00" as a representation for the end of day although it had been permitted in earlier versions of the standard.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A decimal fraction may be added to the lowest order time element present in any of these representations.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A decimal mark, either a comma or a dot on the baseline, is used as a separator between the time element and its fraction.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] There is no limit on the number of decimal places for the decimal fraction.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] However, the number of decimal places needs to be agreed to by the communicating parties.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example, in Microsoft SQL Server, the precision of a decimal fraction is 3 for a DATETIME, i.e., "yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm:ss[.mmm]".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Time zones in ISO 8601 are represented as local time (with the location unspecified), as UTC, or as an offset from UTC.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If no UTC relation information is given with a time representation, the time is assumed to be in local time.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] While it *may* be safe to assume local time when communicating in the same time zone, it is ambiguous when used in communicating across different time zones.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Even within a single geographic time zone, some local times will be ambiguous if the region observes daylight saving time.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It is usually preferable to indicate a time zone (zone designator) using the standard's notation.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If the time is in UTC, add a *Z* directly after the time without a space.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] *Z* is the zone designator for the zero UTC offset.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The *Z* suffix in the ISO 8601 time representation is sometimes referred to as "Zulu time" or "Zulu meridian" because the same letter is used to designate the Zulu time zone.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] However, the ACP 121 standard that defines the list of military time zones makes no mention of UTC and derives the "Zulu time" from the Greenwich Mean Time which was formerly used as the international civil time standard.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] *GMT* is no longer precisely defined by the scientific community and can refer to either UTC or UT1 depending on context.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The UTC offset is appended directly to the time instead of "Z" suffix above; other nautical time zone letters are not used.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The offset is applied to UTC to get the civil time in the designated time zone in the format '±[hh]:[mm]', '±[hh][mm]', or '±[hh]'.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A negative UTC offset describes a time zone west of the prime meridian where the civil time is behind UTC.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] So the zone designation for New York (on standard time) would be "−05:00", "−0500", or "−05".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Conversely, a positive UTC offset describes a time zone east of the prime meridian where the civil time is ahead of UTC.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A time zone where the civil time coincides with UTC is always designated as positive, though the offset is zero (see related specifications below).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] So the zone designation for London (on standard time) would be "+00:00", "+0000", or "+00".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] See List of UTC offsets for other UTC offsets.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It is not permitted to state a zero value time offset with a negative sign, as "−00:00", "−0000", or "−00".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The section dictating sign usage states that a plus sign must be used for a positive or zero value, and a minus sign for a negative value.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A plus-minus-sign (±) may also be used if it is available.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Contrary to this rule, RFC 3339, which is otherwise a profile of ISO 8601, permits the use of "−00" with the same denotation as "+00" but a differing connotation: an unknown UTC offset.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] To represent a negative offset, ISO 8601 specifies using a minus sign (−).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If the interchange character set is limited and does not have a minus sign character, then the hyphen-minus should be used (-).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ASCII does not have a minus sign, so its hyphen-minus character (code 4510) would be used.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If the character set has a minus sign, such as U+2212 − MINUS SIGN in Unicode, then that character should be used.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The HTML character entity invocation for − is `&minus;`.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601-2:2019 allows for general durations for time offsets.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example, more precision can be added to the time offset with the format '<time>±[hh]:[mm]:[ss].[sss]' or '<time>±[n]H[n]M[n]S' as below.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A single point in time can be represented by concatenating a complete date expression, the letter *"T"* as a delimiter, and a valid time expression.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] In ISO 8601:2004 it was permitted to omit the *"T"* character by mutual agreement as in "200704051430", but this provision was removed in ISO 8601-1:2019.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Separating date and time parts with other characters such as space is not allowed in ISO 8601, but allowed in its profile RFC 3339.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If a time zone designator is required, it follows the combined date and time.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Either basic or extended formats may be used, but both date and time must use the same format.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The date expression may be calendar, week, or ordinal, and must use a complete representation.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The time may be represented using a specified reduced precision format.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Durations define the amount of intervening time in a time interval and are represented by the format P[n]Y[n]M[n]DT[n]H[n]M[n]S or P[n]W as shown on the aside.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] In these representations, the [n] is replaced by the value for each of the date and time elements that follow the [n].
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Leading zeros are not required, but the maximum number of digits for each element should be agreed to by the communicating parties.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The capital letters *P*, *Y*, *M*, *W*, *D*, *T*, *H*, *M*, and *S* are designators for each of the date and time elements and are not replaced.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example, "P3Y6M4DT12H30M5S" represents a duration of "three years, six months, four days, twelve hours, thirty minutes, and five seconds".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Date and time elements including their designator may be omitted if their value is zero, and lower-order elements may also be omitted for reduced precision.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example, "P23DT23H" and "P4Y" are both acceptable duration representations.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] However, at least one element must be present, thus "P" is not a valid representation for a duration of 0 seconds.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] "PT0S" or "P0D", however, are both valid and represent the same duration.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] To resolve ambiguity, "P1M" is a one-month duration and "PT1M" is a one-minute duration (note the time designator, T, that precedes the time value).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The smallest value used may also have a decimal fraction, as in "P0.5Y" to indicate half a year.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This decimal fraction may be specified with either a comma or a full stop, as in "P0,5Y" or "P0.5Y".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The standard does not prohibit date and time values in a duration representation from exceeding their "carry over points" except as noted below.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Thus, "PT36H" could be used as well as "P1DT12H" for representing the same duration.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] But keep in mind that "PT36H" is not the same as "P1DT12H" when switching to or from daylight saving time.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Alternatively, a format for duration based on combined date and time representations may be used by agreement between the communicating parties either in the basic format PYYYYMMDDThhmmss or in the extended format P[YYYY]-[MM]-[DD]T[hh]:[mm]:[ss].
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] However, individual date and time values cannot exceed their moduli (e.g. a value of 13 for the month or 25 for the hour would not be permissible).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The standard describes a duration as part of time intervals, which are discussed in the next section.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The duration format on its own is ambiguous regarding the total number of days in a calendar year and calendar month.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The number of seconds in a calendar day is also ambiguous because of leap seconds.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example "P1M" on its own could be 28, 29, 30, or 31 days.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] There is no ambiguity when used in a time interval.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The duration format (or a subset thereof) is widely used independent of time intervals, as with the Java 8 Duration class which supports a subset of the duration format.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A time interval is the intervening time between two time points.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The amount of intervening time is expressed by a duration (as described in the previous section).
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The two time points (start and end) are expressed by either a combined date and time representation or just a date representation.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Of these, the first three require two values separated by an *interval designator* which is usually a solidus (more commonly referred to as a forward slash "/").
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Section 3.2.6 of ISO 8601-1:2019 notes that "A solidus may be replaced by a double hyphen ["--"] by mutual agreement of the communicating partners", and previous versions used notations like "2000--2002".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Use of a double hyphen instead of a solidus allows inclusion in computer filenames; in common operating systems, a solidus is a reserved character and is not allowed in a filename.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For <start>/<end> expressions, if any elements are missing from the end value, they are assumed to be the same as for the start value including the time zone.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This feature of the standard allows for concise representations of time intervals.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If greater precision is desirable to represent the time interval, then more time elements can be added to the representation.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] To explicitly include all of the start and end dates, the interval would be represented as "2007-11-13T00:00/16T00:00".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Repeating intervals are specified in clause "4.5 Recurring time interval".
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] They are formed by adding "R[n]/" to the beginning of an interval expression, where *R* is used as the letter itself and [n] is replaced by the number of repetitions.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Leaving out the value for [n] or specifying a value of -1, means an unbounded number of repetitions.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] A value of 0 for [n] means the interval is not repeated.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If the interval specifies the start (forms 1 and 2 above), then this is the start of the repeating interval.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] If the interval specifies the end but not the start (form 3 above), then this is the end of the repeating interval.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It is based on syntax from iCalendar and shared by IETF RFC 5545.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601:2000 allowed truncation (by agreement), where leading components of a date or time are omitted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Notably, this allowed two-digit years to be used as well as the ambiguous formats YY-MM-DD and YYMMDD.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This provision was removed in ISO 8601:2004.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The first and seventh examples given above omit the leading `-` for century.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Other formats have one leading `-` per omitted century, year, month, week, hour and minute as necessary to disambiguate the format.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601-2:2019 defines a set of standardised extensions to the ISO 8601 date and time formats.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The EDTF is given as an example of a profile of ISO 8601 in Part 2.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It comes in three levels, where level 0 is a subset of Part 1 restricted to extended month–day notation, CCYY-MM-DD, similar to RFC 3339, and levels 1 and 2 build upon that.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] EDTF is mostly tailored to bibliographic and historiographic needs.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The EDTF features are described in the "Date and Time Extensions" section of ISO 8601-2:2019, and the profile itself is found as Annex A.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It is virtually identical to the prior specification pioneered by the US Library of Congress.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] On the Internet, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) uses the IETF standard based on ISO 8601 in defining a profile of the standard that restricts the supported date and time formats to reduce the chance of error and the complexity of software.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The very simple specification is based on a draft of the RFC 3339 mentioned below.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] ISO 8601 is referenced by several specifications, but the full range of options of ISO 8601 is not always used.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] For example, the various electronic program guide standards for TV, digital radio, etc. use several forms to describe points in time and durations.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The ID3 audio meta-data specification also makes use of a subset of ISO 8601.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The X.690 encoding standard's GeneralizedTime makes use of another subset of ISO 8601.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] As of 2006, the ISO week date appears in its basic form on major brand commercial packaging in the United States.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Its appearance depended on the particular packaging, canning, or bottling plant more than any particular brand.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The format is particularly useful for quality assurance, so that production errors can be readily traced.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] IETF RFC 3339 defines a profile of ISO 8601 for use in Internet protocols and standards.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] It explicitly excludes durations and dates before the common era.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The more complex formats such as week numbers and ordinal days are not permitted.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] RFC 3339 deviates from ISO 8601 in allowing a zero time zone offset to be specified as "-00:00", which ISO 8601 forbids.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] RFC 3339 intends "-00:00" to carry the connotation that it is not stating a preferred time zone, whereas the conforming "+00:00" or any non-zero offset connotes that the offset being used is preferred.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This convention regarding "-00:00" is derived from earlier RFCs, such as RFC 2822 which uses it for timestamps in email headers.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] RFC 2822 made no claim that any part of its timestamp format conforms to ISO 8601, and so was free to use this convention without conflict.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Building upon the foundations of RFC 3339, the IETF introduced the Internet Extended Date/Time Format (IXDTF) in RFC 9557.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] This format extends the timestamp representation to include additional information such as an associated time zone name.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] The inclusion of time zone names is particularly useful for applications that need to account for events like daylight saving time transitions.
[src:date-fns-toolkit/iso-8601] Furthermore, IXDTF maintains compatibility with pre-existing syntax for attaching time zone names to timestamps, providing a standardized and flexible approach to timestamp representation on the internet.
